projects.description:
After writing the text for the trailer for Total Mayhem Games's third instalment in the 'We Were Here' series (see: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m3bb0G0pA6E), the team asked me to work with them on the narrative for the full game.

Under the story director, I wrote all original texts related to the narrative and story of the game. Using my background as a historical linguist - with deep knowledge of the medieval language of Middle-Dutch - I was able to add accents of authenticity to the game world, which revolves about an ancient (Dutch) kingdom being frozen in time.

My responsibilities included:
- create various iterations of the plot;
- write dialogue lines for the characters;
- guarantee that each line of dialogue remains sufficiently informative or instructive, to ensure the players maintain focus on their tasks ahead;
- create characters and add to the characterisation of the existing cast;
- write direction lines for the voice actors;
- incorporate the game's lore into my writing;
- check all other writing for consistency;
- help design in-game world items, such as tarot cards;
- insert snippets of Middle-Dutch, to add authenticity;
- think along with the game designers about the puzzles and their place in the game world;
- write rhymes and lyrics for the ominous Jester character.

The challenges I faced were:
- marry the story of the old instalments with the new setting and mechanics of 'We Were Here Together';
- insert as much background story and world building details into the dialogue as the team allowed;
- keep up with the game design's pace of rapid prototyping, meaning that puzzles and sequences I finished writing for might be scrapped from the final game - and filling up the plot issues following said omissions;
- experiment with different rhyme schemes for the Jester's songs;
- hide secret messages in the Jester rhymes.

We Were Here Together is available on Steam: https://store.steampowered.com/app/865360/We_Were_Here_Together/

For Playpal, I worked on mobile health game Keeko. Keeko has the goal of informing the younger generations of healthy habits and stimulates them to change their lifestyle. Examples of health topics the game touches upon are eating healthier and exercising more in a supportive social environment.

I was involved in the design and development process of Keeko early on. This allowed me to set up my vision and plan of execution for the game.

My responsibilities included:
- write an engaging plot for the game;
- expand the existing characters' personalities and design new additions for the cast of heroes, adversaries, and support characters;
- write various iterations of dialogue lines;
- be a consultant on level composition;
- write character background and personalities;
- prepare level designs based on the plot I created;
- write scripts and draw storyboards for the in-game cinematics;
- champion the story and defend its emotional beats.

The challenges I faced were:
- be critical of the world building: monitor the logic and credibility of a version of New York ruled by an evil donut from outer space;
- deal with development challenges and severe loss of core features;

Keeko is out now on the Android store: https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.playpalgames.keekocombatgame

I took on the Game Writing and Narrative Design for the mobile game Mahjong Crimes (Android/iOS) by Spil Games.

By working closely with the game designer, we ensured that the powerful classic story was respectfully translated to the medium of game.

As an admirer of literature, I tried to be as faithful to the source material as possible. Fans of the book will recognise their favourite lines as they play through the game. At the same time, those who first pick up the book after playing the game should already be accustomed to the writing style.

During my work process, I was able to overcome challenges such as:
- grant all 17 characters their moment to shine in the complex murder mystery;
- tinker with the sequence of events for gameplay variety reasons, without spoiling the mystery or hampering the flow of the investigation;
- fit in the plethora of clues, interviews and reveals in the book, in no more than 120 interactions (monologues, dialogues, cinematics);
- keep these lines and interactions as brief as possible; the story could and should not hamper the game.

My responsibilities were to:
- write succinct yet lively dialogue for the puzzle mysteries;
- work within the limits of no more than 8 lines per interaction, spoken by no more than 2 characters; and a character limit of 120 characters per line;
- reshape Agatha Christie’s classic tale to suit a thrilling mobile Mahjong game;
- explain or defend my writing for the licence holders of the Murder on the Orient Express Intellectual Property (Agatha Christie Ltd);
- assist in the editing phase and writing glossaries and tone of voice guides.

I also created an original IP for the game, which has not yet been released.

I was employed by STARK learning to design a story that accompanies a game that is to be used in the class room, in order to have children learn through play. I developed the following products for this game:
- a script for an opening cinematic;
- a script for a closing cinematic;
- texts that will reveal additional story secrets, aimed for use in i.e. loading screens.

The main challenge to offer as much context and information to ensure players' immersion for two animations of max 15 seconds each. This allows students to understand the background of why they are playing this game, as well as stimulate them to bring the game to a satisfying ending by having them empathise with the characters.

All of the products mentioned above were produced in both English and Dutch.

profile_positions.description:
Within the board of the Game Bakery cooperative, I maintain the function of secretary. The cooperative unites game designers and developers, to achieve synergy and to share expertise. Moreover, the cooperative is able to initiate partnerships with other parties, to stimulate our members' professionalisation.

Besides serving its members, the Game Bakery also aims to contribute to other game studios and/or the city of Groningen. We accomplish this by hosting events such as:
- Masterclasses;
- network events;
- showcases for professionals or for anyone who's interested;

but also by contributing or volunteering for broader initiatives and events such as:
- Let's Gro;
- Global Game Jam;
- Playground (Groninger Forum).

Interested in hearing more? Feel free to visit us at Europaweg 8 in Groningen.

Create and edit story content, provide narrative direction, and design game mechanics for the IP team of ADabisc - Future Qatar For Business Development.

I mainly act as Story/Narrative Director for the 'Juniverse' project. To realise my vision for the project, I lead a team of writers and a team of game designers.

My responsibilities include:
- design and improve main and side characters;
- design a quest system and develop content for that system;
- create story context for attractions and edit what others have produced;
- add content to the project's storyworld as well as enrich existing content;
- develop a Story Bible and define writing standards
- design and implement overarching game mechanics for the project;
- plan and execute test sessions, and analyse test results;
- monitor and edit all physical and digital expressions of the story, spread across the various project departments (graphic design, architecture, voice acting, etc.);
- manage my part of the project as product owner (set and keep deadlines, compose progress reports, set quality standards).
